Yes, the JavaScript SDK (@roboflow/inference-sdk) supports these configuration options, but they are set in the StreamConfig object when you initialize your session. Docs

To fix the lag and improve smoothness in JS, add these parameters to your configuration:

1. Enable Real-Time Processing
Ensure realtime_processing is set to true (it is usually true by default). This tells the Roboflow cloud to drop frames if processing falls behind, which prevents the "slow-motion" lag effect.

2. Configure Workflow Parameters
You can pass the source_buffer strategies directly into the workflow_parameters object within your config. This ensures the cloud-side pipeline is running in "Eager" mode.

Example JavaScript Configuration
const config = {
    // High-res requested as you mentioned
    width: 1920,
    height: 1080,
    
    // Smoothness optimizations
    realtime_processing: true, 
    requested_plan: "webrtc-gpu-medium", // Ensure you have enough power for 1080p
    
    // Pass these to the underlying inference engine
    workflow_parameters: {
        "source_buffer_filling_strategy": "DROP_OLDEST",
        "source_buffer_consumption_strategy": "EAGER"
    }
};

// Initialize your stream with the config
const session = await client.webrtc.stream(
    myVideoElement, 
    "your-workflow-id", 
    config
);

3. Important Quality Note (Ramp-up Time)
Because WebRTC uses adaptive congestion control, it can take up to a minute for the stream to reach full 1080p quality and 30 FPS. Docs
 If it looks blurry at first, let it run for ~30-60 seconds to allow the connection to stabilize.

4. GPU Plan
If you are running a heavy workflow (like multiple models or complex visualizations) at 1080p, the default webrtc-gpu-small might struggle. Make sure you are using webrtc-gpu-medium for a smoother experience.

